SIMPLE: translucent
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Translucent
<hw>Trans*lu"cent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>translucens</ets>, <ets>-entis</ets>, p. pr. of
<ets>translucere</ets> to shine through; <ets>trans</ets> across,
through = <ets>lucere</ets> to shine. See <er>Lucid</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Transmitting rays of light without permitting objects
to be distinctly seen; partially transparent.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Transparent; clear.</def> <mark>[Poetic]</mark>
⟦ldquo⟧Fountain or fresh current . . . <xex>translucent</xex>,
pure.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Replenished from the cool, <qex>translucent</qex> springs.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- <er>Translucent</er>, <er>Transparent</er>.</syn>
<usage> A thing is <xex>translucent</xex> when it merely admits the
passage of light, without enabling us to distinguish the color and
outline of objects through it; it is <xex>transparent</xex> when we can
clearly discern objects placed on the other side of it. Glass, water,
etc., are <xex>transparent</xex>; ground glass is
<xex>translucent</xex>; a <xex>translucent</xex> style.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Translucently</ent>⟦br⟧
